<Layout title={title} description={description} schema={schema}>
  <article class="px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Article">
    <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h1>Understanding Property Tax: How It Works</h1>

      <p class="mt-2 flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 not-prose">
        <img src={AUTHOR_PHOTO} alt={AUTHOR_NAME} width="24" height="24" class="rounded-full" loading="lazy" />
        Written by <a href="/about/" class="ml-1 font-medium text-navy-700 hover:underline dark:text-navy-400">{AUTHOR_NAME}</a>
      </p>

      <p>
        Property tax is the largest recurring expense for most homeowners after their mortgage payment, yet
        many people do not understand how it is calculated or that they have options to reduce it. This
        guide explains the mechanics of property tax assessment, common exemptions, how mill rates work,
        and the appeals process available in every state. Whether you are buying a home or managing your
        current tax bill, understanding property tax is essential.
      </p>

      <p>
        Estimate your property tax bill with our <a href="/property-tax-calculator/">property tax
        calculator</a>, and see how property tax compares to income tax in our
        <a href="/guides/state-tax-comparison/">state tax comparison guide</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how-calculated">How Property Tax Is Calculated</h2>

      <p>
        The basic formula for property tax is straightforward:
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Property Tax = Assessed Value x Tax Rate (Mill Rate)</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        However, the details behind each component vary significantly by state and locality.
      </p>

      <h3 id="market-vs-assessed">Market Value vs. Assessed Value</h3>
      <p>
        The <strong>market value</strong> (also called fair market value) is what your property would sell
        for on the open market. The <strong>assessed value</strong> is the value used for tax calculations,
        which may be equal to market value or a percentage of it. Many states use an <strong>assessment
        ratio</strong> that reduces the assessed value:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>100% assessment states:</strong> California, Florida, Idaho, Kentucky (assessed value = market value)</li>
        <li><strong>Partial assessment states:</strong> South Carolina (4% for owner-occupied, 6% for other), Ohio (35%), Georgia (40%), Tennessee (25% residential)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        For example, a home with a market value of $400,000 in South Carolina (owner-occupied) has an
        assessed value of just $16,000 ($400,000 x 4%). The low assessment ratio makes rates appear higher
        but results in a similar tax bill.
      </p>

      <h3 id="mill-rates">Mill Rates Explained</h3>
      <p>
        A <strong>mill</strong> is one-tenth of a cent, or $1 per $1,000 of assessed value. A mill rate of
        25 mills means $25 per $1,000 of assessed value. If your assessed value is $300,000 and the mill
        rate is 25, your property tax is $300,000 / 1,000 x 25 = <strong>$7,500</strong>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Your total mill rate is typically the sum of multiple overlapping taxing jurisdictions:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>County government: 5-15 mills</li>
        <li>City/town government: 3-10 mills</li>
        <li>School district: 10-25 mills (often the largest component)</li>
        <li>Special districts (fire, library, parks): 1-5 mills</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="how-assessed">How Properties Are Assessed</h2>

      <p>
        County assessors use several methods to determine property value:
      </p>

      <h3 id="sales-comparison">Sales Comparison Approach</h3>
      <p>
        The most common method for residential property. The assessor compares your property to similar
        recently sold properties (comparables) in your area, adjusting for differences in size, condition,
        features, and location.
      </p>

      <h3 id="cost-approach">Cost Approach</h3>
      <p>
        Used for unique or new properties. The assessor estimates the cost to rebuild the structure, subtracts
        depreciation, and adds land value.
      </p>

      <h3 id="income-approach">Income Approach</h3>
      <p>
        Used for rental and commercial properties. The assessor estimates the property's income-producing
        potential and applies a capitalization rate to determine value.
      </p>

      <h3 id="reassessment-frequency">Reassessment Frequency</h3>
      <p>
        How often properties are reassessed varies dramatically:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Annual:</strong> Most states reassess every year or on a rolling basis</li>
        <li><strong>Periodic:</strong> Some states reassess every 2-5 years (e.g., Ohio every 3 years)</li>
        <li><strong>Upon sale only:</strong> California (Prop 13) only reassesses when a property is sold or significantly improved, with annual increases capped at 2%</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="exemptions">Common Exemptions That Reduce Your Bill</h2>

      <h3 id="homestead-exemption">Homestead Exemption</h3>
      <p>
        Available in most states for your primary residence. This exempts a portion of your home's value from
        taxation. Examples:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Florida:</strong> First $25,000 exempt from all taxes; additional $25,000 exempt from non-school taxes (total up to $50,000)</li>
        <li><strong>Texas:</strong> $100,000 exemption from school district taxes, plus additional amounts from county/city</li>
        <li><strong>Georgia:</strong> Various exemptions ranging from $2,000 to $10,000 depending on county</li>
        <li><strong>Louisiana:</strong> First $75,000 of assessed value exempt (on a 10% assessment ratio, that covers homes up to $750,000 market value)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 id="senior-exemptions">Senior Citizen Exemptions</h3>
      <p>
        Many states offer additional exemptions or assessment freezes for homeowners aged 65 or older:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Assessment freeze:</strong> Some states freeze the assessed value at the current level so your tax does not increase even if home values rise</li>
        <li><strong>Additional exemptions:</strong> Extra dollar amounts removed from assessed value</li>
        <li><strong>Tax deferrals:</strong> Allow seniors to defer property tax until the home is sold</li>
        <li><strong>Income-based limits:</strong> Some exemptions are only available below certain income thresholds</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 id="veteran-exemptions">Disability and Veteran Exemptions</h3>
      <p>
        Disabled homeowners and veterans (especially those with service-connected disabilities) often qualify
        for significant property tax reductions. Many states exempt 100% disabled veterans from all property
        tax on their primary residence. Surviving spouses may retain the exemption.
      </p>

      <h3 id="agricultural-exemptions">Agricultural and Conservation Exemptions</h3>
      <p>
        Land used for farming, ranching, or conservation purposes may receive a special valuation based on
        agricultural use rather than market value, which is typically much lower. Requirements vary by state
        and usually include minimum acreage and income thresholds.
      </p>

      <h2 id="state-by-state">State-by-State Variation</h2>

      <p>
        Effective property tax rates (actual tax paid as a percentage of market value) vary enormously:
      </p>

