      <h2 id="how-to-appeal">How to Appeal Your Property Tax Assessment</h2>

      <p>
        If you believe your property is over-assessed, you have the right to appeal. Studies suggest that
        30-60% of properties are over-assessed, and roughly half of all appeals result in a reduction. Here
        is the typical process:
      </p>

      <h3 id="appeal-step-1">Step 1: Review Your Assessment Notice</h3>
      <p>
        When you receive your assessment notice (usually annually), check the details carefully: square
        footage, number of bedrooms/bathrooms, lot size, and assessed value. Errors in physical
        characteristics are the easiest to correct.
      </p>

      <h3 id="appeal-step-2">Step 2: Research Comparable Properties</h3>
      <p>
        Look up recent sales of similar homes in your neighborhood. Your assessed value should be in line
        with what similar homes have actually sold for. Online real estate databases, county records, and
        your real estate agent can help.
      </p>

      <h3 id="appeal-step-3">Step 3: File a Formal Appeal</h3>
      <p>
        Contact your county assessor's office for the appeal form and deadline. Most states require appeals
        to be filed within 30-90 days of the assessment notice. Include your evidence: comparable sales data,
        photos of property condition issues, and any errors you found.
      </p>

      <h3 id="appeal-step-4">Step 4: Attend the Hearing</h3>
      <p>
        Present your case to the Board of Equalization or Assessment Review Board. Be prepared, organized,
        and factual. Bring multiple copies of your evidence. Many homeowners successfully represent
        themselves without an attorney.
      </p>

      <h3 id="appeal-step-5">Step 5: Further Appeals</h3>
      <p>
        If the initial appeal is denied, most states allow further appeals to a state tax tribunal or court.
        At this point, hiring a property tax attorney or consultant may be worthwhile if the potential
        savings are significant.
      </p>

      <h2 id="property-tax-federal">Property Tax and Your Federal Taxes</h2>

      <p>
        Property taxes are deductible on your federal income tax return if you itemize deductions. However,
        the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (TCJA) capped the total state and local tax (SALT) deduction at $10,000
        ($5,000 if married filing separately). This cap includes property tax, state income tax, and local
        income tax combined. For taxpayers in high-tax states, this cap significantly limits the benefit.
        See our <a href="/guides/tax-deductions-vs-credits/">deductions vs. credits guide</a> for more.
      </p>

      <h2 id="bottom-line">Bottom Line</h2>

      <p>
        Property tax is a local tax, and rates, assessment methods, and exemptions vary enormously even
        within a single state. Understanding how your bill is calculated gives you the power to claim all
        eligible exemptions and challenge unfair assessments. Use our
        <a href="/property-tax-calculator/">property tax calculator</a> to estimate your liability, and
        consider the property tax impact when comparing states with our
        <a href="/guides/moving-to-a-no-income-tax-state/">no-income-tax state guide</a>.
      </p>
